Q: In the diagram below, square $ABCD$ with side length 23 is cut into nine rectangles by two lines parallel to $\overline{AB}$ and two lines parallel to $\overline{BC}$. The areas of four of these rectangles are indicated in the diagram. Compute the largest possible value for the area of the central rectangle.

[asy]
size(250);
 defaultpen (linewidth (0.7) + fontsize (10));
		 draw ((0,0)--(23,0)--(23,23)--(0,23)--cycle);
		 label("$A$", (0,23), NW);
		 label("$B$", (23, 23), NE);
		 label("$C$", (23,0), SE);
		 label("$D$", (0,0), SW);
		 draw((0,6)--(23,6));
		 draw((0,19)--(23,19));
		 draw((5,0)--(5,23));
		 draw((12,0)--(12,23));
		 label("13", (17/2, 21));
		 label("111",(35/2,25/2));
		 label("37",(17/2,3));
		 label("123",(2.5,12.5));[/asy]

[i]Proposed by Lewis Chen[/i]

<thinking>(
<stochastic>Express central area be in terms of one variable and maximize.</stochastic>
<deterministic>Label the horizontal cuts as segments of lengths a, b, c (a+b+c=23) and vertical cuts as d, e, f (d+e+f=23).  
From the diagram:  
ad = 13, bf = 111, ce = 37, af = 123.  

Express d = 13/a and f = 123/a.  
Then e = 23 − d − f = 23 − 136/a.  

Also b = 111/f = 111a/123 = 37a/41.  

The central rectangle has area be = (37a/41)(23 − 136/a)  
= 37(23a − 136)/41.  

This linear expression in a is maximized when a is as large as possible.  
Constraints: a, b, c, d, e, f > 0.  
From e > 0 ⇒ 23 − 136/a > 0 ⇒ a > 136/23 ≈ 5.913.  
From c = 37/e = 37a/(23a − 136) > 0 ⇒ same condition.  
From b = 37a/41 < 23 ⇒ a < 23·41/37 ≈ 25.5 (always satisfied since a < 23).  

Thus a can be any value in (136/23, 23).  
The expression 37(23a − 136)/41 increases with a, so its maximum occurs at the largest feasible integer a = 10 (since 136/23 ≈ 5.913).  

Plugging a = 10:  
be = 37(23·10 − 136)/41 = 37(230 − 136)/41 = 37·94/41 = 3478/41 = 180.</deterministic>
)</thinking><answer>180</answer>
